    I presume that one of the reasons you want to keep machines private is
    deficient security on them.  I submit that the effort would be better
    spent on improving either the general security of TCP/IP protocols (for
    instance, by implementing Kerberos, or something like it), or the specific
    machines involved. [...]

I have to agree with James that security is never served by obscuring
details -- hiding a machine does not make it less vulnerable to
penetration once it is found.  And it will be found, too, if the cracker
is sufficiently committed to doing so.  He can use exhaustive searches,
or he can penetrate indirectly, through a third-party `trusted' user.

The original note mentioned Multics ACLs as the model for the changes to
the domain name system.  As I remember, Multics was such a secure system
because people [at MIT, anyway] were repeatedly encourage to break into it,
thus revealing all potential pitfalls.  Then again, users didn't have the
brute-force capability then that we do now...

-Philip

